00:08:45.467 --> 00:08:48.500
So let's start out by looking at
the carbon cycle, which is

00:08:48.500 --> 00:08:52.033
really one of the core
issues in the debate.

00:08:52.033 --> 00:08:55.900
It has to do with what controls
the carbon dioxide

00:08:55.900 --> 00:08:57.000
level in the atmosphere.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:01.700
We know the carbon dioxide is
a powerful greenhouse gas.

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:07.267
It has a linear molecular
structure, but it can flap and

00:09:07.267 --> 00:09:12.000
it can vibrate in such
a way to absorb and

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.800
emit infrared radiation.

00:09:14.800 --> 00:09:17.633
So it's a powerful
greenhouse gas.

00:09:17.633 --> 00:09:22.900
It's in part controlled by
anthropogenic processes, so

00:09:22.900 --> 00:09:29.200
it's at the center of
the whole debate.

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:30.633
You have to know this.

00:09:30.633 --> 00:09:35.267
You have to know that when you
burn something like coal, the

00:09:35.267 --> 00:09:42.233
chemical reaction looks like
that, carbon plus oxygen.

00:09:42.233 --> 00:09:45.800
You oxidize the carbon to form
CO2, and that's a gas that

00:09:45.800 --> 00:09:47.867
goes into the atmosphere.

00:09:47.867 --> 00:09:50.567
This comes from the atmosphere,
and this would be

00:09:50.567 --> 00:09:55.267
coming from some buried
deposit of coal.

00:09:55.267 --> 00:10:01.800
If you're burning methane, which
is CH4, you combine that

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:05.867
with oxygen and you get two
by-products, water vapor and

00:10:05.867 --> 00:10:08.000
carbon dioxide.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:13.633
The water vapor we pretty much
neglect, because it goes into

00:10:13.633 --> 00:10:17.833
the atmosphere as water vapor,
but then instantly, it becomes

00:10:17.833 --> 00:10:20.867
part of the normal
hydrologic cycle.

00:10:20.867 --> 00:10:23.867
And if you remember early in
the course, we computed the

00:10:23.867 --> 00:10:27.767
average residence time
for water vapor.

00:10:27.767 --> 00:10:29.167
Anybody remember
what that was?

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.033
Nine days, yeah, eight
days, nine days.

00:10:34.033 --> 00:10:40.067
So in other words, it's cycled
back in rain to the earth's

00:10:40.067 --> 00:10:43.967
surface or the ocean very, very
quickly, and so it really

00:10:43.967 --> 00:10:47.200
plays no role in the
greenhouse effect.

00:10:47.200 --> 00:10:48.200
Let me be careful.

00:10:48.200 --> 00:10:51.867
Water vapor is also a very
powerful greenhouse gas.

00:10:51.867 --> 00:10:55.033
And because there's so much of
it, it's actually in a sense

00:10:55.033 --> 00:10:57.300
the strongest of all the
greenhouse gases.

00:10:57.300 --> 00:11:00.867
But it is controlled by
the natural system.

00:11:00.867 --> 00:11:04.633
It doesn't matter how
much we add into it.

00:11:04.633 --> 00:11:08.933
The level is not going to
change for that reason.

00:11:08.933 --> 00:11:12.267
It's going to be controlled
by the own, the internal

00:11:12.267 --> 00:11:14.133
processes within
the atmosphere.

00:11:14.133 --> 00:11:16.767
Nothing we can do in adding
water vapor is going to have

00:11:16.767 --> 00:11:19.933
any influence on changing the
amount of water vapor in the

00:11:19.933 --> 00:11:21.433
atmosphere.

00:11:21.433 --> 00:11:25.733
So it's important to know that
water vapor is one product,

00:11:25.733 --> 00:11:29.467
but in terms of what that does
to climate, that particular

00:11:29.467 --> 00:11:32.300
piece is negligible
in the sense

00:11:32.300 --> 00:11:34.067
that I have just described.

00:11:36.567 --> 00:11:39.767
Propane is another
form of gas.

00:11:39.767 --> 00:11:43.467
It can be burned for heat,
and the reaction--

00:11:43.467 --> 00:11:45.267
the stoichiometry is a
little bit different.

00:11:45.267 --> 00:11:47.100
I've tried to balance
those reactions.

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:49.900
I'm not a chemist, so you
may want to check me.

00:11:49.900 --> 00:11:53.000
Add up the carbons, add up the
oxygen, be sure everything

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.500
adds up properly, and correct
if I've gone wrong here.

00:11:57.500 --> 00:12:01.433
But basically water
and CO2 again, and

00:12:01.433 --> 00:12:03.700
the same thing implies.

00:12:03.700 --> 00:12:04.967
The CO2 stays in the

00:12:04.967 --> 00:12:09.067
atmosphere, influencing climate.

00:12:09.067 --> 00:12:13.100
The water vapor quickly gets
cycled into the natural

00:12:13.100 --> 00:12:14.467
hydrologic system.

00:12:14.467 --> 00:12:17.767
Another thing that's going on,
we've talked about calcium

00:12:17.767 --> 00:12:22.767
carbonate in this course a
couple of times because that

00:12:22.767 --> 00:12:25.567
excess calcium that we found in
the Quinnipiac River that

00:12:25.567 --> 00:12:30.633
wasn't there in ocean water,
we argued goes into making

00:12:30.633 --> 00:12:33.700
calcium carbonate in
the oceans, shells,

00:12:33.700 --> 00:12:35.067
limestones, and so on.

00:12:35.067 --> 00:12:41.000
There's a lot of that around in
the earth's climate system.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:44.767
If we take a little bit of
that and heat it, we can

00:12:44.767 --> 00:12:49.400
separate it into the material
that's used to make cement,

00:12:49.400 --> 00:12:52.567
but that releases CO2 as well.

00:12:52.567 --> 00:12:54.933
So there's another
source of CO2.

00:12:54.933 --> 00:12:56.533
It's not quite as powerful
as these.

00:12:56.533 --> 00:12:58.500
I'm going to show you some
numbers in a minute.

00:12:58.500 --> 00:13:04.567
But that is another significant
input of CO2, is

00:13:04.567 --> 00:13:09.033
the making of cement from
natural calcium carbonate that

00:13:09.033 --> 00:13:13.633
was precipitated in the oceans
by either living

00:13:13.633 --> 00:13:17.167
or non-living processes.

00:13:17.167 --> 00:13:18.933
Stop me if you have any
questions on this.

00:13:22.400 --> 00:13:26.467
So when you burn fossil fuels
then, you're putting carbon

00:13:26.467 --> 00:13:28.167
dioxide in the atmosphere.

00:13:28.167 --> 00:13:30.700
And that comes from carbon
that's been stored in the

00:13:30.700 --> 00:13:35.867
earth, typically for 60
or 100 million years.

00:13:35.867 --> 00:13:39.467
Remember in the Cretaceous
Period, way back when the

00:13:39.467 --> 00:13:44.000
dinosaurs were alive, that's
when a lot of forests were

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:47.967
being the earth was very warm
during that period of time.

00:13:47.967 --> 00:13:50.533
You had tropical forests almost
everywhere on the

00:13:50.533 --> 00:13:51.667
continents.

00:13:51.667 --> 00:13:54.833
Those trees would
eventually fall.

00:13:54.833 --> 00:13:59.167
And the productivity was so
high, instead of their rotting

00:13:59.167 --> 00:14:01.967
and putting that CO2 back in the
atmosphere, they would be

00:14:01.967 --> 00:14:06.000
covered over by another and
then another and another.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.767
So you ended up sequestering all
of that carbon down in the

00:14:09.767 --> 00:14:13.833
crust of the earth where it's
been sitting there for 60 or

00:14:13.833 --> 00:14:15.733
100 million years.

00:14:15.733 --> 00:14:21.467
And now we're suddenly pulling
it back out and burning it and

00:14:21.467 --> 00:14:24.033
putting it back into
the atmosphere.

00:14:24.033 --> 00:14:28.800
And in the oceans, too,
you had algae growing,

00:14:28.800 --> 00:14:32.967
phytoplankton, that would sink
to the bottom of the ocean,

00:14:32.967 --> 00:14:36.000
and instead of rotting and
returning to the ocean system,

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:37.733
they would get covered over.

00:14:37.733 --> 00:14:43.100
And today you have all of these
oil deposits beneath the

00:14:43.100 --> 00:14:46.533
ocean bottom.

00:14:46.533 --> 00:14:48.333
And then we dig those up
and we burn those, too.

00:14:48.333 --> 00:14:54.967
So both on the land and in the
oceans, we are removing

00:14:54.967 --> 00:14:59.000
ancient, very ancient fossil
carbon and burning it to put

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.667
it back in the atmosphere.

00:15:01.667 --> 00:15:06.467
Now the natural, the
modern biosphere is

00:15:06.467 --> 00:15:07.700
active in this as well.

00:15:11.433 --> 00:15:19.000
For example, trees remove a lot
of carbon dioxide during

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:22.200
the summer season when they're
growing and use that to build

00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:24.200
their woody biomass.

00:15:24.200 --> 00:15:28.933
Remember, the trunk of
a tree is about 1/5

00:15:28.933 --> 00:15:31.500
or one quarter carbon.

00:15:31.500 --> 00:15:33.000
Well, where did that
carbon come from?

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:34.533
It didn't come from the soil.

00:15:34.533 --> 00:15:38.100
From the soil, the tree is
getting water and it's getting

00:15:38.100 --> 00:15:42.500
nutrients, like nitrogens and
phosphorus, but almost all of

00:15:42.500 --> 00:15:46.333
the carbon to build a tree
trunk is coming from the

00:15:46.333 --> 00:15:47.567
atmosphere.

00:15:49.333 --> 00:15:54.900
I mentioned in another context
that I did a project down on a

00:15:54.900 --> 00:15:58.033
small island in the Caribbean
last spring.

00:15:58.033 --> 00:16:00.667
And we were flying an aircraft
around the island.

00:16:00.667 --> 00:16:03.333
One of the sensors we had on
the airplane was a carbon

00:16:03.333 --> 00:16:06.400
dioxide sensor so we could
measure how much carbon

00:16:06.400 --> 00:16:09.533
dioxide was in the atmosphere
upstream of the island, over

00:16:09.533 --> 00:16:12.033
the island, and downstream
of the island.

00:16:12.033 --> 00:16:14.367
The island was forested.

00:16:14.367 --> 00:16:17.000
It's the island of Dominica,
one of the few Caribbean

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:20.833
islands that still has its
original forest. And when we

00:16:20.833 --> 00:16:25.267
flew downstream of the island,
across the wake of the island,

00:16:25.267 --> 00:16:31.500
we found a slight deficit
in carbon dioxide.

00:16:31.500 --> 00:16:34.533
In other words, the air that
had come from upstream and

00:16:34.533 --> 00:16:38.533
passed over the island's forests
had lost a little bit

00:16:38.533 --> 00:16:41.900
of carbon dioxide to those
trees, and we found that

00:16:41.900 --> 00:16:43.733
deficit downwind.

00:16:43.733 --> 00:16:45.733
Now, this has been well known.

00:16:45.733 --> 00:16:48.167
You can measure this in
lots of other ways.

00:16:48.167 --> 00:16:52.900
But this is yet another way to
convince yourself that the

00:16:52.900 --> 00:16:57.367
forests are actively removing
carbon dioxide from the

00:16:57.367 --> 00:17:02.100
atmosphere all the time
that they're growing.

00:17:02.100 --> 00:17:04.067
But then, they recycle
some of that.

00:17:04.067 --> 00:17:08.100
For example, the material in
leaves that falls to earth at

00:17:08.100 --> 00:17:14.100
this time of year then rots and
respires over the winter

00:17:14.100 --> 00:17:17.100
season to put that little
bit of carbon back in.

00:17:17.100 --> 00:17:20.933
Now it still has its woody
biomass, which is most of it,

00:17:20.933 --> 00:17:25.200
but a little bit goes back into
the atmosphere, which

00:17:25.200 --> 00:17:28.567
gives that little bit of wiggle
in the Keeling curve

00:17:28.567 --> 00:17:32.433
that you were studying in
your Time Series Lab.

00:17:32.433 --> 00:17:37.000
So I want to emphasize that the
biosphere is a very active

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:40.300
player in this carbon cycle.

00:17:40.300 --> 00:17:45.567
Certainly on the long term, but
then on the modern time

00:17:45.567 --> 00:17:48.433
scales as well.

00:17:48.433 --> 00:17:50.967
Any questions there?

00:17:50.967 --> 00:17:51.267
Yeah.

00:17:51.267 --> 00:17:54.200
STUDENT: Does the carbon that's
sequestered in the

00:17:54.200 --> 00:17:57.067
wood, when, like, the wood from
the tree rots, is that

00:17:57.067 --> 00:17:59.767
also, is that rereleased
in the atmosphere?

00:17:59.767 --> 00:18:00.300
PROFESSOR:
That's right.

00:18:00.300 --> 00:18:05.933
So if a tree, if a modern tree
today does fall and then you

00:18:05.933 --> 00:18:08.467
watch it over some years, it
rots and kind of disappears

00:18:08.467 --> 00:18:09.167
into the Earth.

00:18:09.167 --> 00:18:12.033
That carbon ends up back
in the atmosphere.

00:18:12.033 --> 00:18:15.733
A little bit may be left in the
soil as organic carbon,

00:18:15.733 --> 00:18:18.333
but then over a longer period
of time, maybe ten or twenty

00:18:18.333 --> 00:18:21.067
years, that too will go back
to the atmosphere.

00:18:21.067 --> 00:18:23.967
So there are few places on
earth, however, where you're

00:18:23.967 --> 00:18:26.267
getting this sequestration,
where you're getting things

00:18:26.267 --> 00:18:29.067
falling on top of it faster
than it can rot.

00:18:29.067 --> 00:18:32.933
But I would say, for example,
in most of these New England

00:18:32.933 --> 00:18:38.633
forests, most of the ancient
tree material is going back

00:18:38.633 --> 00:18:39.867
into the atmosphere.

00:18:44.133 --> 00:18:47.967
Well, in fact, that's one of the
problems with this idea of

00:18:47.967 --> 00:18:50.867
solving the global warming
problem by

00:18:50.867 --> 00:18:53.467
planting lots of trees.

00:18:53.467 --> 00:18:57.500
Because what that will do in the
short run, indeed, it will

00:18:57.500 --> 00:19:00.500
draw extra CO2 from the
atmosphere and store it in the

00:19:00.500 --> 00:19:02.233
biomass of the tree.

00:19:02.233 --> 00:19:06.533
But a typical tree of the
species you're familiar with,

00:19:06.533 --> 00:19:11.633
both conifers and deciduous,
typically have lifetimes of 60

00:19:11.633 --> 00:19:14.333
to 80 to 100 years.

00:19:14.333 --> 00:19:17.233
And then they will fall and
they'll rot and the material

00:19:17.233 --> 00:19:17.700
will go back.

00:19:17.700 --> 00:19:23.767
So it is a temporary fix,
perhaps, to reducing carbon

00:19:23.767 --> 00:19:26.667
dioxide buildup in the
atmosphere, but by no means is

00:19:26.667 --> 00:19:30.167
it permanent because of the
short turnover time of trees

00:19:30.167 --> 00:19:38.633
in the forest.

