So here's what we've
learned from this.

00:31:02.233 --> 00:31:09.233
The biomass is taking in about
half of that extra that we are

00:31:09.233 --> 00:31:11.500
emitting into the atmosphere.

00:31:11.500 --> 00:31:13.667
That's rather remarkable.

00:31:13.667 --> 00:31:18.967
The reason seems to be that
carbon dioxide is in many

00:31:18.967 --> 00:31:25.067
places around the earth and the
ocean a limiting quantity

00:31:25.067 --> 00:31:29.567
for photosynthesis.

00:31:29.567 --> 00:31:33.467
So that when you increase the
concentration of CO2, you

00:31:33.467 --> 00:31:35.967
increase the rate at
which plants grow.

00:31:35.967 --> 00:31:39.733
It's called CO2 fertilization.

00:31:39.733 --> 00:31:44.533
So as CO2 has increased, the
plants have tried to take some

00:31:44.533 --> 00:31:47.467
of that excess back out.

00:31:47.467 --> 00:31:49.233
They take about half
of it out.

00:31:49.233 --> 00:31:52.267
There's some speculation about
whether they will continue to

00:31:52.267 --> 00:31:54.933
be able to take out half,
because they need other

00:31:54.933 --> 00:31:55.767
nutrients as well.

00:31:55.767 --> 00:31:59.000
They need phosphorus and
nitrogen, they need water, if

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:00.900
they're plants growing
on land.

00:32:00.900 --> 00:32:04.067
And it might be that as these
other ingredients become

00:32:04.067 --> 00:32:09.500
limiting, the biosphere will no
longer be able to do this

00:32:09.500 --> 00:32:12.167
for us, and these numbers
could creep up.

00:32:12.167 --> 00:32:15.400
As this one increases, these
might actually creep up

00:32:15.400 --> 00:32:19.433
eventually to become more equal
to the amount that we're

00:32:19.433 --> 00:32:23.100
putting in every year.

00:32:23.100 --> 00:32:24.333
Questions on that?

00:32:27.467 --> 00:32:30.533
So it's interesting to look
at this from a historical

00:32:30.533 --> 00:32:32.567
perspective because what
we're doing now is so

00:32:32.567 --> 00:32:35.033
unusual and so rapid.

00:32:35.033 --> 00:32:37.167
So if we go back 10,000
years, this

00:32:37.167 --> 00:32:38.933
roughly covers the Holocene.

00:32:41.800 --> 00:32:44.333
Here is carbon dioxide
concentration in parts per

00:32:44.333 --> 00:32:45.833
million by volume.

00:32:45.833 --> 00:32:49.700
And of course, the Keeling curve
is the little red part

00:32:49.700 --> 00:32:51.500
here, it's just that
little part.

00:32:51.500 --> 00:32:55.100
Before that time, we get that
data from the ice cores, the

00:32:55.100 --> 00:32:59.733
little vesicles, the little
bubbles in the ice cores give

00:32:59.733 --> 00:33:01.233
us the data prior
to that time.

00:33:01.233 --> 00:33:05.700
But it was pretty flat through
the Holocene, with a value of

00:33:05.700 --> 00:33:11.767
about 270 or 280 or 290
parts per million.

00:33:11.767 --> 00:33:15.067
And then in the Industrial
Revolution, on this time

00:33:15.067 --> 00:33:18.133
scale, it shoots up
almost vertically.

00:33:18.133 --> 00:33:21.200
If you blow that up, blow that
time scale up, and show it

00:33:21.200 --> 00:33:25.267
here going back to 1800, it was
slow at first and then has

00:33:25.267 --> 00:33:29.033
become more and more rapid, as
we discussed in the previous

00:33:29.033 --> 00:33:34.067
couple of diagrams because the
rate of carbon dioxide

00:33:34.067 --> 00:33:35.500
emissions has increased
so strongly.

00:33:38.633 --> 00:33:41.333
We can go back even further
in geologic time.

00:33:44.267 --> 00:33:46.700
And you've seen this kind
of thing before.

00:33:46.700 --> 00:33:55.100
This is an ice core showing
carbon dioxide concentrations.

00:33:55.100 --> 00:34:01.100
Here we are in the Holocene,
right about here, with

00:34:01.100 --> 00:34:05.867
preindustrial levels
around 270 or 280.

00:34:05.867 --> 00:34:09.067
But just prior to that, 15,000,
20,000 years ago at

00:34:09.067 --> 00:34:11.667
the end of last Ice Age, the
values were down about 200

00:34:11.667 --> 00:34:15.900
hundred, and then oscillated
around those lower levels for

00:34:15.900 --> 00:34:18.800
at least 400,000 years.

00:34:18.800 --> 00:34:21.733
It's hard to put this recent
data even on the same scale

00:34:21.733 --> 00:34:25.767
because it plots as almost
a vertical line.

00:34:25.767 --> 00:34:28.333
So the rate at which we're
putting CO2 in and changing

00:34:28.333 --> 00:34:33.033
atmospheric composition is far
higher than anything one could

00:34:33.033 --> 00:34:36.600
diagnose from previous
geologic eras.

00:34:40.267 --> 00:34:44.467
There's another piece to this
argument that I find kind of

00:34:44.467 --> 00:34:45.833
interesting.

00:34:45.833 --> 00:34:48.967
It has to do with the
isotopes of carbon.

00:34:48.967 --> 00:34:54.067
Carbon, like hydrogen and oxygen
that we spoke about

00:34:54.067 --> 00:34:59.333
earlier in the week, come as
a primary element and then

00:34:59.333 --> 00:35:02.433
various heavier isotopes.

00:35:02.433 --> 00:35:05.200
And most carbon is Carbon
12, but there's a

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:06.567
Carbon 13 as well.

00:35:06.567 --> 00:35:09.400
It's a stable isotope
of carbon.

00:35:09.400 --> 00:35:15.500
And the buried fossil fuel
happens to be depleted in

00:35:15.500 --> 00:35:20.633
Carbon 13 relative to the
normal Carbon 12.

00:35:20.633 --> 00:35:27.267
So when we dig up this fossil
fuel and burn it, we're now

00:35:27.267 --> 00:35:32.667
putting a lot of the dominantly
we're putting in

00:35:32.667 --> 00:35:37.733
the Carbon 12 into the
atmosphere, which takes

00:35:37.733 --> 00:35:42.400
whatever fraction we started
with, Carbon 13 to Carbon 12

00:35:42.400 --> 00:35:47.367
in the atmosphere, and making
the overall carbon in the

00:35:47.367 --> 00:35:50.433
atmosphere lighter, because
we're mixing in more of the

00:35:50.433 --> 00:35:54.833
light carbon from the
fossil fuel burning.

00:35:54.833 --> 00:36:01.000
And indeed, if you plot Delta
Carbon 13, using the same kind

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:06.567
of Delta notation we used
before, from 1977 to 2002,

00:36:06.567 --> 00:36:08.033
it's a decreasing number.

00:36:08.033 --> 00:36:10.133
This is data from
the South Pole.

00:36:10.133 --> 00:36:13.300
Here's some data
from Mauna Loa.

00:36:13.300 --> 00:36:17.200
And it shows also a
decreasing trend.

00:36:17.200 --> 00:36:21.867
So some would argue, how do we
know that new carbon dioxide

00:36:21.867 --> 00:36:24.033
in the atmosphere is
coming from the

00:36:24.033 --> 00:36:26.867
burning of fossil fuels?

00:36:26.867 --> 00:36:29.500
Well, one argument would have
been, well we're putting twice

00:36:29.500 --> 00:36:31.500
that much in the atmosphere.

00:36:31.500 --> 00:36:33.000
It makes sense that
at least half of

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:34.900
that would stick around.

00:36:34.900 --> 00:36:36.333
It's a pretty powerful
argument.

00:36:36.333 --> 00:36:38.667
But maybe this is even a more
powerful argument, because

00:36:38.667 --> 00:36:40.733
that carbon we're
putting it has a

00:36:40.733 --> 00:36:43.400
certain isotopic signature.

00:36:43.400 --> 00:36:46.767
And now we see that signature
showing up in

00:36:46.767 --> 00:36:49.300
the atmospheric carbon.

00:36:49.300 --> 00:36:55.200
So it's another argument for the
case that the burning of

00:36:55.200 --> 00:36:58.600
fossil fuels is what's leading
to that increase in carbon

00:36:58.600 --> 00:37:01.633
dioxide in the atmosphere.

00:37:01.633 --> 00:37:02.300
Questions on that.

00:37:02.300 --> 00:37:02.633
Yes?

00:37:02.633 --> 00:37:05.467
STUDENT: Do we know
why it's depleted

00:37:05.467 --> 00:37:07.367
in the heavier isotope?

00:37:07.367 --> 00:37:09.800
PROFESSOR: Yeah, it
has to do with the plants that

00:37:09.800 --> 00:37:12.433
originally took in
that carbon.

00:37:12.433 --> 00:37:16.667
So when a plant grows, as I
mentioned, it takes carbon in

00:37:16.667 --> 00:37:19.100
from the atmosphere to
build its biomass.

00:37:19.100 --> 00:37:23.200
It actually prefers
the light isotope

00:37:23.200 --> 00:37:25.200
over the heavy isotope.

00:37:25.200 --> 00:37:28.633
So when those plants, way back,
100 million years ago,

00:37:28.633 --> 00:37:30.733
were growing their biomass,
they were doing it

00:37:30.733 --> 00:37:33.233
preferentially out
of Carbon 12.

00:37:33.233 --> 00:37:36.933
And then when they got buried,
that left behind a lot of the

00:37:36.933 --> 00:37:38.967
Carbon 13 in the atmosphere.

00:37:38.967 --> 00:37:40.467
They buried a lot of
the Carbon 12.

00:37:40.467 --> 00:37:43.467
Now we're reversing that,
putting the Carbon 12 back in

00:37:43.467 --> 00:37:44.033
the atmosphere.

00:37:44.033 --> 00:37:48.900
So it has to do it how plants
draw in CO2 into their leaves

00:37:48.900 --> 00:37:51.067
and then use that to build
their biomass.

00:37:54.233 --> 00:37:55.467
Good question.

00:37:57.533 --> 00:38:01.467
So let's conclude, then,
our brief discussion

00:38:01.467 --> 00:38:02.767
of the carbon cycle.

00:38:02.767 --> 00:38:05.967
Fossil fuel burning is quickly
returning to the atmosphere

00:38:05.967 --> 00:38:09.800
carbon stored for millions of
years in crustal reservoirs.

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:17.733
About half of the emitted CO2
stays in the atmosphere, and

00:38:17.733 --> 00:38:20.300
we estimate it'll stay there
for at least a few hundred

00:38:20.300 --> 00:38:25.233
years, given the cycling rate
between the biosphere and the

00:38:25.233 --> 00:38:26.300
atmosphere.

00:38:26.300 --> 00:38:31.500
The CO2 emission rate has
increased with time since the

00:38:31.500 --> 00:38:33.300
beginning of the Industrial
Revolution.

00:38:36.133 --> 00:38:39.367
And the current CO2
concentration, which is

00:38:39.367 --> 00:38:43.067
approximately 395 parts per
million by volume, is the

00:38:43.067 --> 00:38:44.600
highest in several
million years.

00:38:44.600 --> 00:38:47.267
Let me be careful of
what I say here.

00:38:47.267 --> 00:38:50.467
If I go back to this diagram,
which shows the last 400,000

00:38:50.467 --> 00:38:55.800
years, clearly, now that we're
up at 390 or 395, that's way

00:38:55.800 --> 00:38:59.533
higher than anything we've
had during the Ice Ages.

00:38:59.533 --> 00:39:05.067
Yet if you go back way earlier,
say 50, 60, 100

00:39:05.067 --> 00:39:08.633
million years ago, you'll find
periods in the earth's history

00:39:08.633 --> 00:39:10.867
where the carbon dioxide
concentration in the

00:39:10.867 --> 00:39:15.133
atmosphere was actually much
higher than it is even today.

00:39:15.133 --> 00:39:17.833
So I don't want to make a
blanket statement saying that

00:39:17.833 --> 00:39:20.400
it's as high as it's
ever been.

00:39:20.400 --> 00:39:26.500
So instead I have said, it is
the highest it's been in

00:39:26.500 --> 00:39:30.000
several million years.

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:35.067
But again, this is the kind of
an argument that arises.

00:39:35.067 --> 00:39:38.867
Someone will say, well, yes,
we're putting a lot of CO2 in

00:39:38.867 --> 00:39:44.033
the atmosphere, but it hasn't
by any means reached an

00:39:44.033 --> 00:39:45.467
unprecedented level.

00:39:45.467 --> 00:39:49.500
There have been periods in the
ancient earth history where

00:39:49.500 --> 00:39:51.267
carbon dioxide concentrations
have been

00:39:51.267 --> 00:39:53.767
much higher than this.

00:39:53.767 --> 00:39:57.633
So it all depends on what you
want to use for your reference

00:39:57.633 --> 00:40:02.567
timeframe as to what kind
of a statement you

00:40:02.567 --> 00:40:03.467
make in this regard.

00:40:03.467 --> 00:40:08.933
So be very careful about that
not to overstate the

00:40:08.933 --> 00:40:15.000
uniqueness of the current carbon
dioxide concentration.

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.267
It's probably safe to say
there's never been a time in

00:40:17.267 --> 00:40:21.967
Earth's history where the CO2 is
increasing as rapidly as it

00:40:21.967 --> 00:40:25.767
is today, where the rate
has been as large.

00:40:25.767 --> 00:40:28.800
But in terms of the absolute
amount, the record we're

00:40:28.800 --> 00:40:32.800
setting now is only the record
for the last few million

00:40:32.800 --> 00:40:36.433
years, not for--certainly not
for all of Earth's history.

00:40:41.733 --> 00:40:45.467
So we've got a couple minutes
to begin the next section,

00:40:45.467 --> 00:40:50.200
which is the Holocene as a
reference time period.

00:40:50.200 --> 00:40:53.767
And I wanted you to be aware
of these particular often

00:40:53.767 --> 00:40:56.000
discussed dates.

00:40:58.667 --> 00:41:04.633
The retreat of the last large
ice sheets was occurring

00:41:04.633 --> 00:41:09.433
around 11,000 years
before present.

00:41:09.433 --> 00:41:11.167
That's right when the
ice was in the

00:41:11.167 --> 00:41:13.800
process of melting back.

00:41:17.367 --> 00:41:20.533
There was a warm period that
followed that called the

00:41:20.533 --> 00:41:25.033
Holocene Optimum about seven to
eight thousand years ago.

00:41:28.867 --> 00:41:32.067
That comes into the argument
when one is trying to find out

00:41:32.067 --> 00:41:36.400
whether the current
warm climate is

00:41:36.400 --> 00:41:38.700
unique even in the Holocene.

00:41:38.700 --> 00:41:42.733
In other words, is our current
climate cooler or warmer than

00:41:42.733 --> 00:41:46.733
this so-called Holocene
Optimum.

00:41:46.733 --> 00:41:50.700
Much more recently, the Medieval
Warm Period, which

00:41:50.700 --> 00:41:55.567
was roughly 1000 A.D.,
is another

00:41:55.567 --> 00:41:56.633
important reference point.

00:41:56.633 --> 00:41:59.500
This, by the way, is the
period when the Vikings

00:41:59.500 --> 00:42:01.500
colonized Greenland.

00:42:01.500 --> 00:42:07.467
There was a warm period when
they could grow crops in the

00:42:07.467 --> 00:42:09.733
coastal regions of Greenland.

00:42:09.733 --> 00:42:15.433
Then came the Little Ice Age
from 1400 to 1800 A.D. I'll

00:42:15.433 --> 00:42:19.167
say a bit more about that.

00:42:19.167 --> 00:42:21.000
And then we get into this
period, as you're seeing in

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:26.033
your data analysis in the lab,
of a more rapid climate change

00:42:26.033 --> 00:42:28.333
over the last hundred
years or so.

00:42:28.333 --> 00:42:30.867
So at the very minimum,
be aware of these.

00:42:30.867 --> 00:42:34.867
And I'll point these out to
you as we look at various

00:42:34.867 --> 00:42:37.800
historical reconstructions
of temperature.

00:42:37.800 --> 00:42:45.567
For example, this one goes back
12,000 years, so that's

00:42:45.567 --> 00:42:47.800
covering most of the Holocene.

00:42:47.800 --> 00:42:50.633
And there's lots of different
data sets represented.

00:42:50.633 --> 00:42:53.600
The black curve is an average
from a number of different

00:42:53.600 --> 00:42:54.900
proxy data sets.

00:42:54.900 --> 00:42:57.900
A proxy data set is where you
haven't measured temperature

00:42:57.900 --> 00:43:01.667
directly with a thermometer,
but you're keeping track of

00:43:01.667 --> 00:43:04.833
something that you think
depends on temperature.

00:43:04.833 --> 00:43:06.000
Maybe it's lake levels.

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:07.333
Maybe it's isotopes.

00:43:07.333 --> 00:43:10.700
Maybe it's there's a lot of
different things you can use.

00:43:10.700 --> 00:43:15.467
They're all called climate
proxies, and they show a lot

00:43:15.467 --> 00:43:18.067
of variability when you average
them together they

00:43:18.067 --> 00:43:20.467
show some trend.

00:43:20.467 --> 00:43:23.000
You see a rapid warming coming
out of the last Ice Age.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:25.167
Then you see this climatic
optimum, what I called the

00:43:25.167 --> 00:43:27.067
Holocene Optimum, right here.

00:43:27.067 --> 00:43:28.667
And then it cooled
off a little bit.

00:43:28.667 --> 00:43:30.833
And then there's some wiggles
near the end that we'll talk

00:43:30.833 --> 00:43:34.667
about in just a minute.

00:43:34.667 --> 00:43:37.500
And again these are plotted
as temperature anomalies.

00:43:37.500 --> 00:43:41.500
They've chosen some period of
time as a reference to compute

00:43:41.500 --> 00:43:43.167
the temperature anomaly.

00:43:45.867 --> 00:43:48.567
This shows the last thousand
years or so.

00:43:48.567 --> 00:43:51.600
So we're looking at a more
recent period of time.

00:43:51.600 --> 00:43:56.467
And this is from the IPCC
report, I think.

00:43:56.467 --> 00:43:58.067
Now I've forgotten
which is which.

00:43:58.067 --> 00:44:03.933
Anyways, these are two different
authors' graphs

00:44:03.933 --> 00:44:08.167
describing the Northern
Hemisphere temperature

00:44:08.167 --> 00:44:11.000
reconstructions for the
last thousand years.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:13.500
And they look a lot alike, but
I wanted to point out some

00:44:13.500 --> 00:44:16.933
differences, because it's on
these differences that many

00:44:16.933 --> 00:44:19.667
arguments will be built.

00:44:19.667 --> 00:44:22.467
For example, this author
has shown a lot of

00:44:22.467 --> 00:44:25.867
the different proxies.

00:44:25.867 --> 00:44:28.867
And if you average those
together, you'd probably get

00:44:28.867 --> 00:44:31.900
something that rose a little
bit in this period of time,

00:44:31.900 --> 00:44:33.733
then sank a little bit more.

00:44:33.733 --> 00:44:36.867
Here's the Little Ice Age, a
little cooler in this period

00:44:36.867 --> 00:44:41.900
of time, and then you get the
rapid rise and rise again.

00:44:41.900 --> 00:44:47.800
This author has suppressed all
the different proxies and

00:44:47.800 --> 00:44:50.867
instead just shown the standard

00:44:50.867 --> 00:44:54.200
deviation in the data.

00:44:54.200 --> 00:44:57.567
I think it's like the two
sigma and the one sigma.

00:44:57.567 --> 00:45:00.700
And while he does show a little
bit of a rise, the way

00:45:00.700 --> 00:45:03.400
he's plotted it gives you the
idea that this is more of a

00:45:03.400 --> 00:45:08.033
straight line, maybe slightly
decreasing, and then rising

00:45:08.033 --> 00:45:08.800
rapidly at the end.

00:45:08.800 --> 00:45:15.267
By the way, this is the famous
hockey stick diagram.

00:45:15.267 --> 00:45:20.967
Because that shape looks a
bit like a hockey stick.

00:45:20.967 --> 00:45:23.933
It used to be, twenty years ago,
when you Google hockey

00:45:23.933 --> 00:45:30.500
stick, all you would get would
be websites about hockey.

00:45:30.500 --> 00:45:32.900
Now when you Google hockey
stick, you get hockey and you

00:45:32.900 --> 00:45:36.800
get climate change because of
all the controversy over this.

00:45:36.800 --> 00:45:40.233
The author this original
diagram, Mike Mann, was a PhD

00:45:40.233 --> 00:45:41.000
from our department.

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:42.867
In fact, I sat on
his committee.

00:45:42.867 --> 00:45:44.967
This wasn't in his thesis,
it was in following work.

00:45:44.967 --> 00:45:48.233
But I've tried to follow
the arguments.

00:45:48.233 --> 00:45:53.333
The poor guy has been badgered
by the right wing anti-global

00:45:53.333 --> 00:45:55.467
warming crowd incessantly.

00:45:55.467 --> 00:45:58.533
Because the implication of this
diagram is that what's

00:45:58.533 --> 00:46:03.700
happened in the past hundred
years is unique in regards to

00:46:03.700 --> 00:46:05.900
what's happened over the
last thousand years.

00:46:05.900 --> 00:46:08.267
But it seems to me you'd get
that impression from this

00:46:08.267 --> 00:46:11.233
curve as well, even though
they've given you more of a

00:46:11.233 --> 00:46:15.867
warming period in here, in
Medieval Warm Period.

00:46:15.867 --> 00:46:18.933
Still, what's happening today
in steepness and in height

00:46:18.933 --> 00:46:20.033
seems to be unique.

00:46:20.033 --> 00:46:26.167
So all the arguments and the
dispute over the details of

00:46:26.167 --> 00:46:29.567
how this diagram were
constructed seem to be kind of

00:46:29.567 --> 00:46:32.767
moot now because we see
